Not a fan of the whole  aspect of this at all. It cheapens the trauma that would come naturally with seeing your favorite pet torn apart (coming from someone who has such a pet), and is something that usually gets laughed at when included in an article. I feel like there was a subconscious fixation on eyes in this article simply for the body horror, even if it could be only because of the visual hallucination property.

I'm also not a fan of the tests reiterating what was already established in the description. I was also a little confused by the addendum, as they don't actually list what the context for each one is besides a  (which also reiterates the description), an email that should have been included as information in the final test, and a 3rd addenda that could have been a single sentence.

There also doesn't seem to be any deep motive behind killing non-pet owners, when I would think they get off scot-free for not  or something like that. I think death is used too often to attempt to get a scare out of the reader, since essentially anyone exposed to it dies.

I do think that the the tire and remains on it makes for an interesting object for the basis article, and how it was vague in what exactly had died on it certainly more interesting than a panther. This seems to be in the positives, but I would rewrite it from the ground up.

-1





